But first he speakes of affliction alone, and then of comfort alone. If we be afflicted, it is for your good, and if we be comforted it is for your good. His reason is; because sometimes afflictions appeare without comfort: therefore he saith not, If we be comforted onely it is for your good, but if we be afflicted it is for your good. Sometimes comfort is before our afflictions, that we may indure it the better God cheares us to it;


Sometimes God sheds his Spirit in affliction, that there is abundance of comfort in it: but for the most part it comes after, after we have waited: but in it there is always such a measure of comfort, that supports us that we sink not: yet the speciall degree of comfort usually comes after; therefore he speaks of affliction in the first place.


If I be afflicted it is for you, &c.

Our rejoycing is this. The word in the originall is more then joy: for it is (
   〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
) a glorying, our glorying is this, which is a joy manifesting Doct. Christians have their joy. it self in the outward man, when the heart and the spirit seeme as it were to go outward, and (as it were) to meet the thing joyed in. A Christian hath his joy, his glorying, and a glorying that is proper to himself: it is a spirituall joy, as it followes after, Our rejoycing is the testimony of our conscience.
